    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load metric.csv. Consider only rows whose cmdb_id is one of the candidate service components: ['carts','catalogue','orders','payment','user']. For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) compute: total point count and the global P95 of value using the entire available series (do NOT filter by time before computing P95). Return a compact table of these (cmdb_id, kpi_name, count, p95) ordered by count desc (limit 50 rows).\nThen filter metric.csv to the incident window [2024-01-19 14:49:49 UTC, 2024-01-19 15:19:49 UTC] (use pd.to_datetime(..., unit='s', utc=True) for timestamp parsing). Using the previously computed global P95 per (cmdb_id,kpi_name), mark points in the incident window as anomalous if value >= P95 (for KPIs where higher is worse) or value <= P05 if you believe lower-is-worse KPIs exist (but for now treat anomaly as >= P95). Produce two outputs:\n1) anomaly_summary: per (cmdb_id,kpi_name) within the incident window, report anomaly_count, total_points_in_window, earliest_anomaly_timestamp (as ISO UTC string), and p95. Limit rows to top 50 ordered by anomaly_count desc.\n2) anomaly_rows: list anomaly rows within the incident window with columns (timestamp (ISO UTC), cmdb_id, kpi_name, value, p95). Limit to the first 50 rows ordered by timestamp asc.\nReturn these two tables plus the thresholds table from above. Keep outputs compact."
}

{
    "analysis": "Previous step results: global P95 thresholds were computed for 34 (cmdb_id, kpi_name) groups for candidate services. After filtering to the incident window (2024-01-19T14:49:49Z – 2024-01-19T15:19:49Z) we found coincident anomalies starting at ~2024-01-19T14:52:00Z. The strongest metric signals are: (1) catalogue.socket, user.socket (25/25 points > P95), and payment.socket (9/25 > P95) — suggesting socket/network issues across multiple services; and (2) a large carts.diskio spike at 14:52Z (value 74061 > P95 ~59249) — suggesting an I/O event on carts. Many error-count KPIs have global P95 = 0.0, which caused misleading anomaly flags when using >=P95; those error-count results should be treated cautiously. trace.csv and error_logs.csv are empty, so we cannot use traces or error log contents to disambiguate. We therefore need to use log.csv (application logs) to see traffic (row_count) drops or error spikes across services during the window to decide whether the root cause is network/socket-related or a carts disk I/O problem. Specifically, we should check per-service log.row_count for drops (<= global P05) and spikes (>= global P95) and log.error_count for positive errors (>0) within the incident window. This will help localize the root cause service and reason.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load log.csv. For each (cmdb_id, log_name) compute global P95 and P05 across the entire file (do NOT filter by incident time). Then filter log rows to the incident window [2024-01-19 14:49:49 UTC, 2024-01-19 15:19:49 UTC] and for each (cmdb_id, log_name) compute: total_points_in_window, count_low = number of points with value <= P05, earliest_low_timestamp (ISO UTC) or None, count_high = number of points with value >= P95, earliest_high_timestamp (ISO UTC) or None, count_error_positive = number of points with value > 0 (only relevant for log.error_count), earliest_error_timestamp (ISO UTC) or None. Return a compact table with columns (cmdb_id, log_name, p95, p05, total_points_in_window, count_low, earliest_low_timestamp, count_high, earliest_high_timestamp, count_error_positive, earliest_error_timestamp). Limit output to top 20 rows ordered by max(count_low,count_high,count_error_positive) desc."
}

Based on the metric and log analysis, the most likely root cause is a carts disk I/O spike starting at 2024-01-19 14:52:00 UTC causing downstream throughput degradation and secondary socket symptoms.

